1.6   Terminal Branches of the Brachial Plexus

Next, identify the terminal branches, of the brachial plexus, as follows:
TAKE TURNS pointing to the various roots, trunks and cords of the brachial
Place a probe or a finger underneath the lateral and medial cords and the nerves that arise from them, and notice that they form the shape of the letter “M”    .

Identify the musculocutaneous nerve (C5-C6) as the continuation of the lateral cord. 
Identify the median nerve (C6-T1) in the middle     , formed by contributions from both the lateral and medial cord.
Identify the ulnar nerve (C8-T1) as the continuation of the medial cord.
I’ve highlighted this in the diagram on this slide, in red.

Now, gently move these cords and nerves aside and isolate the posterior cord. Observe that the posterior cord gives rise to the axillary nerve (C5-C6) before continuing as the radial nerve (C5-T1). 
Notice, that the spinal levels that contribute to a terminal branch may be a subset of those contained within the cord(s) that gives rise to it!
Put a moist cloth over the prosection for now.
